To set the initial state object `userData` to an empty object and update it with a new key-value pair in a React.js application, you can follow these steps:

1. In your component, define the initial state using the `useState` hook:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const [userData, setUserData] = useState({});

  // Rest of the component code
}
```

2. To update the state with a new key-value pair, you can use the `setUserData` function:

```jsx
setUserData(prevState => ({
  ...prevState,
  newKey: newValue
}));
```

For example, if you want to add a new key `"name"` with the value `"John"` to the `userData` object, you can use:

```jsx
setUserData(prevState => ({
  ...prevState,
  name: "John"
}));
```

Note that by using the spread operator `...prevState`, you're creating a new object with all the existing key-value pairs in `userData` and then adding the new key-value pair.

Here's a complete example of how it can be done:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const [userData, setUserData] = useState({});

  const handleUpdateUserData = () => {
    setUserData(prevState => ({
      ...prevState,
      name: "John"
    }));
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={handleUpdateUserData}>Update User Data</button>
      <pre>{JSON.stringify(userData, null, 2)}</pre>
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, when you click the "Update User Data" button, the `userData` state will be updated with the new key `"name"` and its value will be `"John"`. The updated `userData` state will be displayed in a `pre` tag.

