```java
public static int calculateSum(int x, int y) {
    while (y != 0) {
        int carry = x & y;
        x = x ^ y;
        y = carry << 1;
    }
    return x;
}
```

Explanation:

The method uses a while loop to keep adding the carry value to the sum of x and y until the carry value becomes zero.

In each iteration of the loop, the carry value is calculated by performing a bitwise AND operation on x and y.

The sum of x and y is calculated by performing a bitwise XOR operation on x and y.

The carry value is shifted to the left by one position using the bitwise left shift operator (<<) to get it ready for the next iteration.

Finally, the method returns the resulting sum of x and y.

This implementation can handle negative integers because the bitwise operators work with the two's complement representation of integers.

It can also handle cases where the sum of x and y exceeds the maximum value of an int because the carry value is shifted to the left and added to the sum in each iteration. This allows the sum to "overflow" into the higher bits, effectively handling cases where the result exceeds the maximum value of an int.

