Here's an implementation of a basic calculator in Java that supports addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations. It also handles parentheses for grouping expressions and supports floating-point numbers. It includes a history feature that stores previous calculations and allows the user to retrieve them.

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
import java.util.Stack;

public class Calculator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        String input;
        Stack<String> history = new Stack<>();

        System.out.println("Basic Calculator");
        System.out.println("Supported operations: +, -, *, /");
        System.out.println("Enter 'history' to view previous calculations");
        System.out.println("Enter 'exit' to exit the calculator");

        while (true) {
            System.out.print("Enter an expression: ");
            input = scanner.nextLine();

            if (input.equalsIgnoreCase("exit")) {
                break;
            } else if (input.equalsIgnoreCase("history")) {
                if (history.isEmpty()) {
                    System.out.println("No previous calculations");
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Previous calculations:");
                    for (String calculation : history) {
                        System.out.println(calculation);
                    }
                }
                continue;
            }

            double result;
            try {
                result = evaluateExpression(input);
                System.out.println("Result: " + result);
                history.push(input + " = " + result);
            } catch (Exception e) {
                System.out.println("Invalid expression. Please try again.");
            }
        }
    }

    public static double evaluateExpression(String expression) {
        expression = expression.replaceAll("\\s+", ""); // Remove all whitespaces from the expression

        // Check if the expression is a single number
        if (expression.matches("[-+]?\\d*\\.?\\d+")) {
            return Double.parseDouble(expression);
        }

        // Create two stacks to store numbers and operators
        Stack<Double> numbers = new Stack<>();
        Stack<Character> operators = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < expression.length(); i++) {
            char ch = expression.charAt(i);

            // If the current character is a number, push it to the numbers stack
            if (Character.isDigit(ch) || ch == '.') {
                StringBuilder num = new StringBuilder();

                while (i < expression.length() && (Character.isDigit(expression.charAt(i)) || expression.charAt(i) == '.')) {
                    num.append(expression.charAt(i));
                    i++;
                }

                i--;

                numbers.push(Double.parseDouble(num.toString()));
            } else if (ch == '(') {
                operators.push(ch);
            } else if (ch == ')') {
                while (operators.peek() != '(') {
                    numbers.push(applyOperation(operators.pop(), numbers.pop(), numbers.pop()));
                }
                operators.pop();
            } else if (ch == '+' || ch == '-' || ch == '*' || ch == '/') {
                while (!operators.isEmpty() && hasPrecedence(ch, operators.peek())) {
                    numbers.push(applyOperation(operators.pop(), numbers.pop(), numbers.pop()));
                }
                operators.push(ch);
            }
        }

        while (!operators.isEmpty()) {
            numbers.push(applyOperation(operators.pop(), numbers.pop(), numbers.pop()));
        }

        return numbers.pop();
    }

    public static boolean hasPrecedence(char op1, char op2) {
        if (op2 == '(' || op2 == ')') {
            return false;
        }

        return (op1 == '*' || op1 == '/') || (op2 == '+' || op2 == '-');
    }

    public static double applyOperation(char operator, double b, double a) {
        switch (operator) {
            case '+':
                return a + b;
            case '-':
                return a - b;
            case '*':
                return a * b;
            case '/':
                if (b == 0) {
                    throw new ArithmeticException("Division by zero");
                }
                return a / b;
            default:
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid operator");
        }
    }
}
```

You can run the above code to use the calculator. It will prompt you to enter an expression and will display the result. You can enter 'history' to view the previous calculations and 'exit' to exit the calculator.

Here's an implementation of the reverseArray function that handles arrays with nested arrays or objects as elements:

```javascript
function reverseArray(array) {
  let reversedArray = [];

  for (let i = array.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    if (Array.isArray(array[i])) {
      reversedArray.push(reverseArray(array[i])); // Recursive call for nested arrays
    } else if (typeof array[i] === 'object') {
      reversedArray.push(reverseObject(array[i])); // Helper function for reversing objects
    } else {
      reversedArray.push(array[i]);
    }
  }

  return reversedArray;
}

function reverseObject(object) {
  let reversedObject = {};

  for (let key in object) {
    if (Array.isArray(object[key])) {
      reversedObject[key] = reverseArray(object[key]); // Recursive call for nested arrays in objects
    } else if (typeof object[key] === 'object') {
      reversedObject[key] = reverseObject(object[key]); // Recursive call for nested objects
    } else {
      reversedObject[key] = object[key];
    }
  }

  return reversedObject;
}
```

This implementation uses a recursive approach to handle nested arrays and objects. The reverseArray function takes an input array and creates an empty reversedArray. It then iterates over the elements of the input array in reverse order, and for each element, checks if it is an array or an object. If it is an array, it recursively calls reverseArray to reverse the nested array, and if it is an object, it calls the helper function reverseObject to reverse the object. If the element is neither an array nor an object, it is directly pushed into the reversedArray.

The reverseObject function takes an input object and creates an empty reversedObject. It then iterates over the properties of the input object, and for each property, checks if its value is an array or an object. If it is an array, it recursively calls reverseArray to reverse the nested array, and if it is an object, it recursively calls reverseObject to reverse the nested object. If the value is neither an array nor an object, it is directly assigned to the corresponding property in the reversedObject.

This implementation has a time complexity of O(n^2 * m), where n is the length of the input array and m is the maximum depth of nested arrays or objects. The recursive calls to reverseArray and reverseObject are made for each nested array or object, resulting in the time complexity being proportional to n^2 * m.

