To get the current battery level in Android, you can use the BroadcastReceiver class along with the Intent.ACTION_BATTERY_CHANGED action. This will allow you to listen for changes in the battery state and extract the battery level from the received intent.

Here's an example of how you can create a function to get the current battery level, handling cases where the device is plugged in and charging:

```java
import android.content.BroadcastReceiver;
import android.content.Context;
import android.content.Intent;
import android.content.IntentFilter;
import android.os.BatteryManager;

public class BatteryUtils {

    private static BroadcastReceiver batteryReceiver;

    public static void startBatteryMonitoring(Context context, final OnBatteryLevelChangedListener listener) {
        IntentFilter filter = new IntentFilter(Intent.ACTION_BATTERY_CHANGED);
        batteryReceiver = new BroadcastReceiver() {
            @Override
            public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
                int level = intent.getIntExtra(BatteryManager.EXTRA_LEVEL, -1);
                int scale = intent.getIntExtra(BatteryManager.EXTRA_SCALE, -1);
                int batteryLevel = (int) (level * 100f / scale);
                boolean isCharging = intent.getIntExtra(BatteryManager.EXTRA_PLUGGED, -1) > 0;

                // If the device is charging, set the battery level to 100
                if (isCharging) {
                    batteryLevel = 100;
                }

                listener.onBatteryLevelChanged(batteryLevel);
            }
        };

        context.registerReceiver(batteryReceiver, filter);
    }

    public static void stopBatteryMonitoring(Context context) {
        if (batteryReceiver != null) {
            context.unregisterReceiver(batteryReceiver);
            batteryReceiver = null;
        }
    }

    public interface OnBatteryLevelChangedListener {
        void onBatteryLevelChanged(int batteryLevel);
    }
}
```

To use this function, you need to implement the OnBatteryLevelChangedListener interface and pass an instance of it to the startBatteryMonitoring function. Whenever the battery level changes, the onBatteryLevelChanged method will be called with the updated battery level.

Here's an example of how you can use the BatteryUtils class:

```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity implements BatteryUtils.OnBatteryLevelChangedListener {

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        BatteryUtils.startBatteryMonitoring(this, this);
    }

    @Override
    public void onBatteryLevelChanged(int batteryLevel) {
        // Do something with the battery level
        Log.d("Battery Level", String.valueOf(batteryLevel));
    }

    @Override
    protected void onDestroy() {
        BatteryUtils.stopBatteryMonitoring(this);
        super.onDestroy();
    }
}
```

In the above example, the onBatteryLevelChanged method will be called whenever the battery level changes, even when the device is plugged in and charging.

