Here is a Java program that finds the longest increasing subsequence in an array, where the subsequence must have a minimum length of 3 and the array can contain duplicate elements:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class LongestIncreasingSubsequence {
    public static List<Integer> findLongestIncreasingSubsequence(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int[] dp = new int[n];
        int maxLength = 0;
        int endIndex = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            dp[i] = 1;
            for (int j = 0; j < i; j++) {
                if (nums[i] > nums[j] && dp[j] + 1 > dp[i]) {
                    dp[i] = dp[j] + 1;
                }
            }
            if (dp[i] > maxLength) {
                maxLength = dp[i];
                endIndex = i;
            }
        }

        List<Integer> longestIncreasingSubsequence = new ArrayList<>();
        longestIncreasingSubsequence.add(nums[endIndex]);

        while (maxLength > 1) {
            maxLength--;
            endIndex--;
            while (endIndex >= 0) {
                if (nums[endIndex] < nums[endIndex + 1] && dp[endIndex] == maxLength) {
                    longestIncreasingSubsequence.add(nums[endIndex]);
                    break;
                }
                endIndex--;
            }
        }

        return longestIncreasingSubsequence;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {1, 4, 2, 3, 7, 4, 5, 6, 8};
        List<Integer> longestIncreasingSubsequence = findLongestIncreasingSubsequence(nums);

        System.out.println("Longest increasing subsequence:");
        for (int i = longestIncreasingSubsequence.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            System.out.print(longestIncreasingSubsequence.get(i) + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

This program uses dynamic programming to find the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at each index. It then finds the maximum length and its corresponding index. Finally, it reconstructs the subsequence by iterating backwards from the end index and adding elements to the list.

Note that the time complexity of this program is O(n^2), where n is the length of the input array.

