Here is the code in Java to calculate the minimum number of coins needed to make change for a given amount:

```java
public class CoinChange {
    public static int minimumCoins(int[] denominations, int amount) {
        int[] dp = new int[amount + 1];
        Arrays.fill(dp, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        dp[0] = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i <= amount; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < denominations.length; j++) {
                if (denominations[j] <= i && dp[i - denominations[j]] != Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
                    dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i], dp[i - denominations[j]] + 1);
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[amount] == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : dp[amount];
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] denominations = {1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50};
        int amount = 34;
        int minimumCoins = minimumCoins(denominations, amount);
        System.out.println("Minimum number of coins needed: " + minimumCoins);
    }
}
```

The code uses dynamic programming to calculate the minimum number of coins needed to make change for a given amount. It initializes an array `dp` with size `amount + 1` and fills it with `Integer.MAX_VALUE` as an initial value. Then, it iterates over the values from 1 to `amount` and for each value, it checks if using each coin denomination can result in a smaller number of coins. If so, it updates the value in the `dp` array. Finally, it returns `dp[amount]` if it is not equal to `Integer.MAX_VALUE`, otherwise, it returns -1.

