Here is one way to implement a password validator in Java:

```java
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class PasswordValidator {
    private static final String SPECIAL_CHARACTERS = "!@#$%^&*()-_+={}[]|\\:;\"'<>,.?/`";

    public static boolean validatePassword(String password) {
        if (password.contains(" ")) {
            return false;
        }

        if (isPalindrome(password)) {
            return false;
        }

        if (!containsUppercase(password) || !containsLowercase(password) || !containsDigit(password) || !containsSpecialCharacter(password)) {
            return false;
        }

        if (containsConsecutiveRepeatingCharacters(password)) {
            return false;
        }

        return true;
    }

    private static boolean isPalindrome(String password) {
        StringBuilder reversed = new StringBuilder(password).reverse();
        return password.equals(reversed.toString());
    }

    private static boolean containsUppercase(String password) {
        return !password.equals(password.toLowerCase());
    }

    private static boolean containsLowercase(String password) {
        return !password.equals(password.toUpperCase());
    }

    private static boolean containsDigit(String password) {
        return password.matches(".*\\d.*");
    }

    private static boolean containsSpecialCharacter(String password) {
        return Pattern.compile("[" + Pattern.quote(SPECIAL_CHARACTERS) + "]").matcher(password).find();
    }

    private static boolean containsConsecutiveRepeatingCharacters(String password) {
        for (int i = 0; i < password.length() - 1; i++) {
            if (password.charAt(i) == password.charAt(i + 1)) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(validatePassword("Passw0rd!")); // true
        System.out.println(validatePassword("Password1")); // false
        System.out.println(validatePassword("password")); // false
    }
}
```

This implementation uses regular expressions to check for the presence of uppercase letters, lowercase letters, digits, and special characters. The `containsUppercase`, `containsLowercase`, `containsDigit`, and `containsSpecialCharacter` methods each return `true` if the corresponding character type is present in the password.

The `isPalindrome` method checks if the password is the same forwards and backwards by reversing it and comparing it to the original password.

The `containsConsecutiveRepeatingCharacters` method iterates through the password and checks if any consecutive characters are the same.

The `validatePassword` method checks each requirement one by one and returns `false` if any requirement is not met. If all requirements are met, it returns `true`.

In the `main` method, a few example passwords are validated and the results are printed.

