Here's the implementation of the `countOccurrences` function:

```javascript
function countOccurrences(webpageContent, searchText) {
  let count = 0;
  let searchLen = searchText.length;
  let contentLen = webpageContent.length;

  for (let i = 0; i <= contentLen - searchLen; i++) {
    let match = true;

    for (let j = 0; j < searchLen; j++) {
      if (webpageContent[i + j] !== searchText[j]) {
        match = false;
        break;
      }
    }

    if (match) {
      count++;
    }
  }

  return count;
}
```

In this function, we first initialize the count variable to 0. We also calculate the lengths of the search text and the webpage content.

We then use a nested loop to iterate through the webpage content. The outer loop iterates from 0 to `contentLen - searchLen` to ensure that we don't go out of bounds while searching for the text. The inner loop compares each character of the search text with the corresponding character in the webpage content. If there is a mismatch, we break out of the inner loop and move on to the next iteration of the outer loop.

If all characters of the search text match, we increment the count variable by 1.

Finally, we return the count, which represents the number of times the search text appears in the webpage content.

