When parsing a deeply nested JSON string in JavaScript, you can optimize for performance and minimize memory usage by using a streaming JSON parser instead of the default `JSON.parse()` method. Streaming parsers process the JSON string incrementally, allowing you to handle each token as it is parsed, rather than loading the entire JSON into memory.

One popular library for streaming JSON parsing in JavaScript is `jsonstream` (https://www.npmjs.com/package/jsonstream). Here's an example of how you can use it:

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const JSONStream = require('jsonstream');

const stream = fs.createReadStream('data.json')
  .pipe(JSONStream.parse('path.to.array.*'))
  .on('data', (data) => {
    // Handle each parsed object here
    console.log(data);
  })
  .on('end', () => {
    // Parsing complete
  })
  .on('error', (err) => {
    // Handle any parsing errors here
    console.error(err);
  });
```

In the example above, `jsonstream` parses the JSON string incrementally and emits a 'data' event for each object found at the specified path (`path.to.array.*`). This way, you can process each object one by one, minimizing memory usage.

Remember to replace `'data.json'` with the path to your actual JSON file or pass a JSON string directly if you have it in memory.

Alternatively, if you're working with a JSON string already in memory, you can use `JSONStream.parse()` directly on the string instead of using a file stream.

Using a streaming JSON parser like `jsonstream` allows you to parse deeply nested JSON strings efficiently, especially when dealing with large data sets.

